the git credentials are updated yet the old github user is being recognized

That happens a lot on Windows—Git is still using cached credentials from your old GitHub account even after you update user.name and user.email.

👉 Important:
user.name and user.email are only for commits, not authentication. The push still uses stored credentials.

✅ Fix: Remove old cached credentials
🔹 Method 1: Windows Credential Manager (most common fix)
Press Start → search Credential Manager

Go to Windows Credentials

Find entries like:

git:https://github.com
Remove them

🔹 Method 2: Git command (quick way)
Run:

git credential-manager reject https://github.com
🔹 Then push again
git push
Now Git will ask for:

Username → your new GitHub username

Password → your Personal Access Token (PAT) (not your password)

🔹 Double-check remote repo (important)
Sometimes you're pushing to a repo owned by the old user:

git remote -v
If needed, update it:

git remote set-url origin https://github.com/NEW_USERNAME/REPO_NAME.git
🔹 Optional (best fix): Switch to SSH
Avoid this problem forever:

ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "your@email.com"
Then add the key to GitHub and change remote to:

git remote set-url origin git@github.com:USERNAME/REPO.git
🚨 Why this happens
Git caches credentials in Windows

Changing config ≠ changing login

So it silently keeps using old account

