how to remove contributors in the github project

Removing contributors on GitHub can mean two different things—so here’s the correct approach depending on what you want:

🔹 1. Remove a collaborator (stop their access) ✅
If you want to stop someone from accessing your repo:

Steps:
Go to your repository on GitHub

Click Settings

Click Collaborators (or Manage access)

Find the user

Click Remove access

👉 This removes their ability to push code.

🔹 2. Remove someone from “Contributors” list ❗
This is different—and tricky.

👉 GitHub automatically shows contributors based on commit history.
You cannot directly remove them unless you change history.

✅ Ways to remove a contributor from the list
🔸 Option A: Rewrite Git history (advanced ⚠️)
You must remove or change their commits:

Using tools like:

git rebase

git filter-repo (recommended)

Example (change email/author):

git filter-repo --commit-callback '
if commit.author_email == "old@email.com":
    commit.author_name = "New Name"
    commit.author_email = "new@email.com"
'
Then force push:

git push --force
👉 This rewrites history and removes them from contributors.

🔸 Option B: Start fresh repo (easy)
Create a new repo on GitHub

Copy code (without .git folder)

Push again

👉 Only you will appear as contributor.

🔸 Option C: Squash commits
If their commits are merged:

git rebase -i HEAD~X
Then squash commits into yours.

🚨 Important warnings
Rewriting history can break projects for others

Avoid if working in a team

Always backup before force push

💡 Quick summary
Remove access → Settings → Collaborators

Remove from contributors → Rewrite history or new repo

